05181nam a22006495i 9780822389903DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223899037 a10.1515/97808223899032doi  a(DE-B1597)554685  a(OCoLC)1224279235  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHN733.5b.R67 2007 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.70951/0905112221 aRofel, Lisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDesiring China :bExperiments in Neoliberalism, Sexuality, and Public Culture /cLisa Rofel; ed. by Lisa Lowe, Judith Halberstam. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerverse Modernities: A Series Edited by Jack Halberstam and Lisa Lowe : 2000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Yearnings: Televisual Love and Melodramatic Politics -- t2. Museum as Women’s Space: Displays of Gender -- t3. Qualities of Desire: Imagining Gay Identities -- t4. From Sacrifice to Desire: Cosmopolitanism with Chinese Characteristics -- t5. Legislating Desire: Homosexuality, Intellectual Property Rights, and Consumer Fraud -- t6. Desiring China: China’s Entry into the WTO -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough window displays, newspapers, soap operas, gay bars, and other public culture venues, Chinese citizens are negotiating what it means to be cosmopolitan citizens of the world, with appropriate needs, aspirations, and longings. Lisa Rofel argues that the creation of such “desiring subjects” is at the core of China’s contingent, piece-by-piece reconfiguration of its relationship to a post-socialist world. In a study at once ethnographic, historical, and theoretical, she contends that neoliberal subjectivities are created through the production of various desires—material, sexual, and affective—and that it is largely through their engagements with public culture that people in China are imagining and practicing appropriate desires for the post-Mao era.Drawing on her research over the past two decades among urban residents and rural migrants in Hangzhou and Beijing, Rofel analyzes the meanings that individuals attach to various public cultural phenomena and what their interpretations say about their understandings of post-socialist China and their roles within it. She locates the first broad-based public debate about post-Mao social changes in the passionate dialogues about the popular 1991 television soap opera Yearnings. She describes how the emergence of gay identities and practices in China reveals connections to a transnational network of lesbians and gay men at the same time that it brings urban/rural and class divisions to the fore. The 1999–2001 negotiations over China’s entry into the World Trade Organization; a controversial women’s museum; the ways that young single women portray their longings in relation to the privations they imagine their mothers experienced; adjudications of the limits of self-interest in court cases related to homoerotic desire, intellectual property, and consumer fraud—Rofel reveals all of these as sites where desiring subjects come into being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCosmopolitanismzChina. 0aCulture and globalizationzChina. 0aHomosexualityxSocial aspectszChina. 0aNational characteristics, Chinese. 0aNeoliberalismzChina. 0aPopular culturezChina. 0aPost-communismzChina. 0aSexxSocial aspectszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aHalberstam, Judith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLowe, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.lo